`}<img alt={"img"} src={require("!url-loader?limit=10000&name=assets/images/[name]-[hash].[ext]&fallback=file-loader!./../static/img/cmp_number_train_4.png").default} /></p>
    <p>{`In order to understand this claim better let's look at a specific example below, for training with `}<strong parentName="p">{`1-3 subjects`}</strong>{` we can see that the `}<strong parentName="p">{`baseline performance is low`}</strong>{` on the right plot and with more training data the baseline performance is higher. Whereas when we look at the performance of the model after adding the `}<strong parentName="p">{`1200 samples`}</strong>{` using active learning the one with less training data(`}<em parentName="p">{`blue,green and red dotted line`}</em>{`) on the left plot is able to personalize better. This is an interesting observation and indicates a tradeoff between baseline performance vs personalization.`}</p>
    <p><img alt={"img"} src={require("!url-loader?limit=10000&name=assets/images/[name]-[hash].[ext]&fallback=file-loader!./../static/img/cmp_tradeoff.png").default} /></p>
